title: For Sale:  Pre 64 Winchester 70 NM 7mm 15x42 Weaver Apex C&R
postcontent: 1956 Winchester Model 70 in 7mm Rem Mag. Winchester used this stock on their National Match, Heavy Weight Target Model & the Bull Guns. It is big & beefy; black walnut, long & wide beavertail forend, large pistol grip, rounded comb with large fluted area, finely checkered steel target butt plate, 1 ¼” wide military type sling swivels, adjustable base for forward sling rest. It is un-checkered & has a hand rubbed oil finish which shows off the gorgeous swirled grain with stripes & bird-eyes. There are no cracks or repairs, no noticeable handling marks, beautiful condition. The LOP is 13 ¼”, drop @ comb is 1 3/6”, drop @ heel is 1 11/16”; all correct according to Roger Rules Book on Model 70’s. The receiver has the original finish, no finish wear, excellent condition. The bolt serial number matches, it slotted for clip loading, which by 1956 was only on the 3 models mentioned above. The rifle has a 24” Apex “no sights” heavy barrel with a target crown & is free floating in stock. The taper goes from 1.19” at receiver to .93” at muzzle. No bluing wear just a couple of small handling marks. Mechanically sound; functions properly & safely with a smooth action. The bore is bright & shiny with no frosting, looks like new. The trigger pull is 4 pounds with no creep, just right. Topped off with a 15x42 Weaver rifle scope; excellent condition, crystal clear optics, adjustable eye relief, duplex crosshairs & an adjustable field of vision. Heavy barrel model 70’s are rare & 7mm Rem Mag was not offered in any Pre-64 Model 70. The only way to get one was to have it re-barreled. This is a true one of a kind in excellent or near mint condition.

It is a full-size polymer frame semi-automatic pistol chambered in the potent .22 Magum round. It comes with (2) 30-round capacity magazine's and factory case and manual. That's a lot of firepower and plinking fun, for such a light weight pistol. This gun is perfect for your “Bug Out Bag.” A careful distribution of polymer and aluminum around key steel components has reduced the pistol's weight to a feathery 13.6 ounces when unloaded. A fully loaded magazine will only add 6 more ounces to the total weight. The pistol has a narrow profile overall. The front-to-back distance in the grip is a bit longer than usual in order to accommodate the .22 Mag. cartridges. The full-length grip also has a subtle pie-wedge shape, narrowing at the front under the trigger guard. The overall effect is a grip that is quite comfortable to work with, even for shooters with smaller hands. The PMR-30 has an ambidextrous safety that is easy to reach and operate. The slide arrives from the factory fitted with bright fiber-optic sites, and it's drilled and tapped to accommodate a scope base. The frame has an integrated Picatinny accessory rail to allow shooters to attach various lights and laser sights. I also have 100 rounds of .22 WMR ammo that I will sell with the gun for an extra $30.
